      <title>“听蝼蛄叫还不种庄稼了？”</title>
      <link href="/2020/07/06/%E2%80%9C%E5%90%AC%E8%9D%BC%E8%9B%84%E5%8F%AB%E8%BF%98%E4%B8%8D%E7%A7%8D%E5%BA%84%E7%A8%BC%E4%BA%86%EF%BC%9F%E2%80%9D/"/>
      <url>/2020/07/06/%E2%80%9C%E5%90%AC%E8%9D%BC%E8%9B%84%E5%8F%AB%E8%BF%98%E4%B8%8D%E7%A7%8D%E5%BA%84%E7%A8%BC%E4%BA%86%EF%BC%9F%E2%80%9D/</url>
      
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<blockquote><p><em>There were many mole crickets and we could hear them chirp at night. There was a popular expression among us: “Don’t stop planting wheat just because mole crickets chirp,” which means you should not let little problems or risks prevent you from doing what is necessary. I still follow such wisdom today.</em>  Weijian Shan <em>Out of the Gobi</em></p></blockquote><p><img src="https://s1.ax1x.com/2020/07/06/UPJU4P.jpg" alt="UPJU4P.jpg"></p><p>去年初秋翻到这一段时心中忽有所悟，暗下决心要完成一桩拖了很久的事情，到本月初终于告成。聊记一笔。</p>]]></content>
      
      
